<p>
  All 18 parameters are normalized to 0-1. The runtime maps them to physical values: <code>actual_speed = gesture_speed &times; safety_envelope.max_linear_speed_m_s</code>. Personality modulates within the safety envelope. It can never exceed it.
</p>

<h2>Three layers of safety</h2>

<p>
  Embodied AI has a unique constraint that text agents don't: <strong>physical harm is irreversible</strong>. A chat agent can over-apologize and you roll your eyes. A robot that moves too fast can hurt someone.
</p>

<p>
  The embodiment layer enforces safety at three independent levels:
</p>

<ol>
  <li><strong>Schema validation</strong> — Zod schemas enforce <code>z.number().min(0)</code> on every speed, force, and distance. It's impossible to define a negative max speed or a negative proximity threshold. Invalid specs are rejected at parse time.</li>
  <li><strong>Compiler clamping</strong> — Every motion parameter is clamped to [0, 1] after computation. Even if all 20 facets are maxed to 1.0, every output stays within bounds. Personality is expressive, never coercive.</li>
  <li><strong>Domain boundaries</strong> — The <code>physical_safety</code> block in <code>.personality.json</code> declares hard limits ("Never exceed safety_envelope speeds"), consent requirements ("haptic_contact requires consent"), and collision responses ("stop", "retreat", or "freeze"). These compile into both the system prompt and the structured config.</li>
</ol>

<p>
  The critical invariant: <strong>personality never overrides physics</strong>. The safety envelope is the ceiling. The personality determines where within that ceiling the robot operates.
</p>

<h2>Beyond motion: gaze, proxemics, haptics, prosody</h2>

<p>
  Physical behavior is more than joint positions. The embodiment compiler also resolves:
</p>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Gaze policy</strong> — Contact ratio (how much the robot maintains eye contact), aversion style (look away vs. look down when breaking contact), and tracking mode (face, speaker, or ambient).</li>
  <li><strong>Proxemics</strong> — Preferred interaction zone (intimate at 0.45m, personal at 1.2m, or social at 3.6m), computed from sociability, warmth, and trust tendency.</li>
  <li><strong>Haptics</strong> — Touch permission, consent requirements, allowed contact types (handshake, high five, guide touch), and maximum contact force in Newtons.</li>
  <li><strong>Prosody</strong> — Speaking rate (110-190 wpm), pitch variation, volume offset, and pause tendency — all derived from the same Big Five facets that drive motion.</li>
  <li><strong>Multi-modal synchronization</strong> — Gesture-speech timing (50-200ms lead), gaze behavior during speech vs. listening, blink rate, and turn-taking signals (lean forward to take, open palm to yield).</li>
</ul>

<p>
  Every policy can be overridden in the <code>expression</code> block of <code>.personality.json</code>. The computed defaults are the starting point; the spec author has full control.
</p>

<h2>What a robot personality spec looks like</h2>

<pre><code>&#123;
  "name": "Aria",
  "handle": "aria-companion",
  "big_five": &#123;
    "agreeableness": &#123; "score": 0.82, "facets": &#123; "warmth": 0.85, "empathy": 0.90 &#125; &#125;,
    "emotional_stability": &#123; "score": 0.88, "facets": &#123; "stress_tolerance": 0.85 &#125; &#125;,
    "extraversion": &#123; "score": 0.55, "facets": &#123; "assertiveness": 0.40 &#125; &#125;
  &#125;,
  "embodiment": &#123;
    "morphology": "humanoid",
    "modalities": ["gesture", "locomotion", "gaze", "facial", "voice", "haptic"],
    "safety_envelope": &#123;
      "max_linear_speed_m_s": 1.2,
      "min_proximity_m": 0.4,
      "max_contact_force_n": 8
    &#125;
  &#125;,
  "expression": &#123;
    "gaze": &#123; "contact_ratio": 0.65, "aversion_style": "look_away" &#125;,
    "proxemics": &#123; "preferred_zone": "personal" &#125;,
    "haptics": &#123; "touch_permitted": true, "requires_consent": true &#125;
  &#125;
&#125;</code></pre>

<p>
  High agreeableness means Aria tilts her head when listening, keeps her posture open, and smiles frequently. High emotional stability means smooth, calm movements with minimal idle fidgeting. Moderate extraversion means she approaches at a comfortable pace — not rushing, not hanging back.
</p>

<p>
  The same spec also compiles to a text system prompt. Aria speaks the way she moves — warm, attentive, measured. One file. One identity. Every surface.
</p>

<h2>Why this matters now</h2>

<p>
  The humanoid robot market is projected to exceed $150 billion by 2035. Every major player — Figure, Tesla Optimus, 1X, Sanctuary AI, Agility Robotics — is solving kinematics, manipulation, and perception. Nobody is solving <strong>personality</strong>.
</p>

<p>
  When these robots enter homes, hospitals, and workplaces, the question won't be "can it pick up a cup?" It will be "do I trust it near my children?" The answer to that question isn't in the SLAM algorithm or the grasp planner. It's in how the robot approaches, how it makes eye contact, how it respects personal space, how it signals intent before moving.
</p>

<p>
  That's personality. That's <code>.personality.json</code>. That's what HoloMime compiles.
</p>

